  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much does it cost to buy a flight simulator?",
  "response": "The cost of buying a flight simulator can vary significantly based on the type, quality, and complexity of the simulator you are looking for. Here are some general categories and their price ranges:\n\n1. **Desktop Flight Simulators:**\n   - Basic home flight simulator software (like Microsoft Flight Simulator or X-Plane) typically ranges from $60 to $120.\n   - Additional hardware, like joysticks, yokes, and rudder pedals, can cost anywhere from $50 to several hundred dollars, depending on the quality and features.\n\n2. **Mid-Range Flight Simulators:**\n   - More advanced setups with better hardware, multi-monitor setups, and additional peripherals can range from $1,000 to $5,000. This often includes high-end flight controls and immersive experiences.\n\n3. **Professional Flight Simulators:**\n   - Professional-grade simulators used for training can cost tens of thousands to millions of dollars. For example, full-motion simulators used by airlines and training facilities can start at around $500,000 and can exceed $10 million.\n\n4. **DIY Simulators:**\n   - Building a custom simulator can be more cost-effective, depending on your choices of hardware. Costs can range from a few hundred dollars for a basic setup to thousands for a more advanced, realistic experience.\n\n5. **Virtual Reality (VR) Simulators:**\n   - VR setups can enhance simulation experiences, with VR headsets costing between $300 to $1,000, plus the cost of a computer capable of running the software smoothly.\n\nWhen considering a flight simulator, it's essential to think about what you're looking to achieve\u2014casual enjoyment versus serious training\u2014and budget accordingly.",
